posts.com:
I exclusively listen to CDs, I might use youtube to demo some stuff but don't really consider myself having heard the album until I hear it on my dedicated transport, dac, and amp. Haven't had a hard drive library in a decade. And I refuse to have to rely on someone from some private trackers' EAC rips, fuck that. This is important to me, so money is no issue for this sort of thing, $60 goa trance CD? no problem, $100 g-funk CD, no problem, $200 dungeon synth CD, no problem. Traveling the country searching record stores, no problem. It pays to own the shit.

I remember back when I didn't have shit going for me, I used to not eat and forego insurance and other basic necessities to build the collection. The space and
money have forced me to have higher standards and a good understanding of my taste. It forces me to really know all of these albums in and out. I remember exact places, times, what the weather was like, etc where I found each of my CDs. Very emotional connection to the music.

Look into constructing a beginners practice routine, one that works for your level, musical goals and time contraints. only if the frets are defective.
here's a QRD
>straighten truss rod to lower action at frets 1-5 or so
>lower saddles or bridge (depending on bass) to lower action at frets 12+
>if you get too much fret buzz at frets 1-5, loosen truss rod until it gets better
>if you get too much fret buzz at frets 12+, raise saddle/bridge until it gets better
truss rod adjustments may take a while to take effect because the wood in the neck needs time to reset
and after you're done adjusting, you will need to fix intonation by moving the saddles forward/backward until both the open string and 12th fret octave are in tune

>>114033249
Frankly, that's part of why Magma is by far my favorite zeuhl act, and not just because they were my first one. Haven't listened to Bondage Fruit yet, but I'm familiar with the other three bands you listed and like them a lot, but the chaos and energy they go for kinda misses out on that more otherworldy celestial vibe that Magma typically goes for. I think part of it is that they mostly hone in on the prog and rock elements, but most of Magma is very consciously informed by Carl Orff and John Coltrane, which is part of what makes zeuhl "Zeuhl" in the first place. I guess it's kinda ironic that the progenitors of this subgenre are actually the least accessible to some prog fans.
And just to warn you, their albums from 2004 and onwards after their reunion only get less "prog rock" sounding. The electric guitar becomes more of an afterthought, and a bigger emphasis is placed on the vocal harmonies.

Yes, Offering is great. While I definitely prefer Magma, I love that Vander's vocals play a larger role, and his drumming definitely sounds more like Rashied Ali or Elvin Jones in particular parts, which fits the mood so well. The more loose spiritual jazz structure is a nice take on the kind of music that inspired Zeuhl in the first place. The John/Alice Coltrane influence is even more apparent, and in such a beautiful and wholesome way. Outside of jazz, it's perhaps the closest a band has come to reaching that same sense of awe or beauty as A Love Supreme. While Part I/Part II is good, I definitely prefer the later albums. The song you linked is majestic.

>>114058963
1) It didn't fit into traditional European classical harmonic theory. Prior to the late 18th century classical music was very strict in regards to how chords could be built and voiced, and what their functions were (ie. how they could be placed in a progression and how their tensions had to be resolved). Beginning with the Romantic period, composers sought more expressive freedom within the structures and forms of classical, and began a process of undermining and challenging the "rules" composers, theorists and critics historically used to analyse and compose. Schoenberg comes very late in this story, and arguably ended this period of experimentation with serialism.
2) Basically none when it comes to 12TET music. There are some musicians that experiment with microtonality to produce new chords, but the number of people who can really hear and distinguish those kinds of chords is relatively small. Check out Jacob Collier if you're interested in that, though I can't say I'm a huge fan.

>>114050375
Pic related + Fux will take you a very long way.

Mortenson and the other partimento guys like Gjerdingen explain baroque and classical as being assembled out of a bunch of stock harmonic gestures (openers, moves within the key like the circle of 5ths progrssion, cadences, sequences for modulating, progressions for variations, etc) and a zillion ideas on how to elaborate on them. Also explains how to write in all the solo keyboard styles of time - different types of preludes, variations (and how to come up with decent variations), arias, and the suite forms. All of it is taught to you in a way that makes it possible to improvise in these styles - I dont really have the chops to do this beyond preluding, but it's just as useful for learning to compose in as least-intimidating of a way as possible. The compendium of stylistically appropriate 18th century harmonic progressions alone makes this book extremely valuable. He's also got a book on improvising fugue coming out next month.

it's mostly not that interesting
Phaidia get some credit for being possibly the first Japanese deathrock band, but mostly they're only notable because Tatsuya Yoshida was the drummer before he was in YBO2 or Ruins
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lXqKwxe6kFw
G-Schmitt is okay but they're kinda Siouxsie-lite
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-H4RMHmV6m8
Auto-Mod is okay. they released 4 albums in 1985. IIRC each one had a different lineup and different sound
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TouLKHa97yI
Kokushoku Elegy is okay. Singer Kyoko was later in OOIOO
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vREw6Xvdlgc
Sadie Sads were really good, sorta an overproduced version of The Birthday Party
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NC5c_4rk0to
Ill Bone is kinda meh
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mHKxoUimYp0
Bardo Thödol, ZOA, etc. are are also kinda meh
most of the bands appeared on Transrecords https://www.discogs.com/label/84511-Transrecords-2
or Wechselbalg Syndicate https://www.discogs.com/label/96095-Wechselbalg-Syndicate

*before anybody suggests I listen to serious folk music, I do.
